rch for therapy in changing conditions. Mobile individuals, ideas and materials played key roles in medical networks that involved both professionals and laypeople. These networks connected colonial medicine with Protestant Christianity and migrant labour.The book will be of value to scholars and students of history and anthropology of colonialism and medicine, as well as a wider readership interested in the plural search for health in Africa and globally.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aStudies in Imperialism 2017. 7aHISTORY / Africa / Central.2bisacsh  aAfrican medicine.  aDavid Livingstone.  aMalawian-British Protestant mission.  aWestern medicine.  aZambesi expedition.  aantimalarials.  aill health.  aindigenous healers.  amedical cultures.  amedical middles.  amorbidity.  aquinine.  asecular medicine.  aspiritual medicine.1 aHokkanen, Markku, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2017 eBook-Packagez978311128281740uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152612389340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526123893423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526123893/original  a978-3-11-128281-7  Manchester University Press 2017 eBook-Packageb2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles